---
description: Code style conventions for JavaScript, TypeScript, Python, Ruby, and Shell
globs: *.js,*.jsx,*.ts,*.tsx,*.py,*.rb,*.sh,*.zsh,*.bash,*.go
alwaysApply: false
---

JavaScript/TypeScript: Use function definitions for top-level functions, not arrow functions (e.g. `function handleClick(event: FullyQualifiedType) { ... }`). All JSDoc must include types exhaustively.

Python: Use Python 3.14 for all repos; set `requires-python = ">=3.14"`, `mypy python_version = "3.14"`, `basedpyright pythonVersion = "3.14"`, and `ruff target-version = "py314"` in `pyproject.toml`. Build with `hatchling` and manage dependencies with `uv` using `[dependency-groups] dev` (not `[project.optional-dependencies]`). Every MCP server repo needs a one-touch `install.sh` and an up-to-date `README.md` with prerequisites, setup, and development instructions. Every function, method, parameter, and return type must be fully typed with parameterized generics (`dict[str, float]`, `list[CsvRow]`, `Callable[[str], bool]`); `Any` and `object` are banned as type annotations, so use `JsonValue`, a concrete union, or a Pydantic model instead, and narrow types at boundaries with `isinstance`, `TypeGuard`, or Pydantic `model_validate`. Use Pydantic `BaseModel` for all structured data; use `Field(alias="camelCase")` with `model_config = ConfigDict(populate_by_name=True)` when field names must match an external API's camelCase wire format, use snake_case for Python field names with attribute-style access, and use `model_dump(by_alias=True)` when serializing back. Start every module with `from __future__ import annotations`; set line length to 90 and let `ruff format` handle wrapping; use explicit `if`/`else` blocks instead of ternaries; use explicit loops instead of nested or multi-clause comprehensions (single-clause comprehensions are fine when they fit naturally on one line); write full-word variable names like `attempt_count` and `error_message` (single-letter names are fine for numeric loop indices `i`/`j`/`k`); extract literal values into named constants; and when a linter rule fires, fix the code or restructure it so the rule no longer applies. Write readable code by breaking complex expressions into intermediate variables with descriptive names and extracting repeated patterns into functions or utilities. Run `make check` before committing: `mypy` (strict, `disallow_any_explicit`, `disallow_any_generics`, `disallow_subclassing_any`) enforces full typing; `basedpyright` (strict) replaces `pyright` and adds stricter defaults; `ruff check` enforces import order, naming, and patterns with rule sets `F`, `E`, `W`, `I`, `N`, `UP`, `ANN`, `B`, `A`, `C4`, `RET`, `SIM`, `TC`, `PYI`, `PT`, `RUF` (ignored: `TC001`, `TC003`, `RET504`, `SIM108`, `N815`); `ruff format` owns all whitespace; `ban-object` (`scripts/ban_object.py`) rejects bare `object` in type annotations; and `make fmt` runs `ruff format` and `ruff check --fix`.

Git: Always use `origin/main` (not `main`) for diffs, merge-base, log ranges, and branch comparisons in worktrees, since the local `main` ref is checked out elsewhere and goes stale after every fetch.

Ruby: Use one guard clause per condition (e.g. `return unless x`, `return unless y`, `return if z`).

Cross-language scripts: When code calls out to a different language (AppleScript via `osascript`, SQL, shell via `subprocess`, etc.), write the script in its own file with the appropriate extension (`.applescript`, `.sql`, `.sh`), then load the file at runtime and substitute dynamic values using the host language's templating primitives (e.g. `string.Template` in Python). This keeps each language in its own file where editors, linters, and syntax highlighting work correctly.

Shell: Use a shebang (`#!/usr/bin/env bash` or `#!/usr/bin/env zsh`), snake_case for functions and local variables, UPPER_CASE for globals and constants, 4-space indentation, and `[[...]]` for tests; scope variables with `local` inside functions, use `source` instead of `.`, and add shellcheck directives when they help. For conditionals, use a full `if / then / fi` block; use a single-line `|| return 1` or `|| exit 1` for guard clauses on missing prerequisites; and use `|| true` for intentionally best-effort calls. Scripts that spawn background processes must trap INT/TERM, track PIDs in an array, have the trap handler kill them, check an interrupt flag each iteration in long-running loops, exit with 130 after handling INT, and clean up temp files and dirs in the trap handler.

Code comments: Add comments only when the code is not self-explanatory. Keep comments technical and explain the "why" behind non-obvious decisions.
